1
00:00:32,407 --> 00:00:35,618
ALL CHARACTERS, ORGANIZATIONS, PLACES, AND
ASSOCIATIONS IN THIS DRAMA ARE FICTITIOUS

2
00:00:38,538 --> 00:00:41,166
-What's wrong?
-He must not be feeling well.

3
00:00:49,299 --> 00:00:51,092
Dr. Cha, are you okay?

4
00:01:14,866 --> 00:01:15,950
Dr. Cha.

5
00:01:23,541 --> 00:01:24,751
I'm here.

6
00:01:29,756 --> 00:01:30,965
Let me take over.

7
00:01:34,010 --> 00:01:35,386
You are seeing me for real.

8
00:01:52,112 --> 00:01:53,238
Let me do it.

9
00:01:54,197 --> 00:01:55,365
You can trust me.

10
00:02:06,668 --> 00:02:07,836
I apologize...

11
00:02:08,837 --> 00:02:10,171
for the unexpected situation.

12
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:15,009
This is the second-year resident
in our department

13
00:02:15,135 --> 00:02:17,470
who I just talked about.

14
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:18,972
She is more ambitious...

15
00:02:20,265 --> 00:02:21,516
than you might think.

16
00:02:21,766 --> 00:02:23,685
As she gave me the crucial hint,

17
00:02:23,810 --> 00:02:24,936
she must...

18
00:02:25,812 --> 00:02:27,856
want to explain it herself.

19
00:02:30,275 --> 00:02:31,359
Let's hear it.

20
00:03:11,691 --> 00:03:13,026
I'm a second-year resident...

21
00:03:13,735 --> 00:03:16,404
at Seoul Hanse Medical Center's
Anesthesiology Department.

22
00:03:16,529 --> 00:03:17,739
My name is Kang Si-young.

23
00:03:17,989 --> 00:03:20,158
I can explain this part for you...

24
00:03:21,117 --> 00:03:24,787
because I got a hint
from a patient I once treated.

25
00:03:30,835 --> 00:03:32,045
The patient complained

26
00:03:32,128 --> 00:03:34,339
of stinging and burning pains

27
00:03:34,464 --> 00:03:35,924
across a large part of his body

28
00:03:36,007 --> 00:03:38,343
including his chest, shoulders, and arms.

29
00:03:39,427 --> 00:03:42,555
In the end, he was diagnosed
with zoster sine herpete.

30
00:03:42,805 --> 00:03:43,932
Let me help you.

31
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:47,644
You monitor
your unresponsive body endlessly,

32
00:03:47,894 --> 00:03:50,271
and even have to hide the fact
that you're doing so.

33
00:03:50,688 --> 00:03:51,689
Let me help you.

34
00:03:52,607 --> 00:03:54,067
I'll do everything that I can.

35
00:03:56,945 --> 00:03:59,197
I got a hint during that process.

36
00:04:00,073 --> 00:04:03,034
Dr. Cha just mentioned...

37
00:04:03,451 --> 00:04:05,453
that he felt pain
because there was no pain.

38
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:07,664
And the hint is related to that.

39
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:10,750
ZINMU RIJUND

40
00:04:13,086 --> 00:04:14,921
May I help you?

41
00:04:15,922 --> 00:04:17,840
HAN MIN-JU
ZINMU RIJUND SALES TEAM

42
00:04:18,383 --> 00:04:19,676
Death Talks.

43
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:22,553
-Pardon?
-I'm a patient member there.

44
00:04:27,725 --> 00:04:28,851
This.

45
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:33,147
I thought it looked familiar.
I think I saw it at Death Talks.

46
00:04:33,731 --> 00:04:34,774
That's right.

47
00:04:35,149 --> 00:04:38,945
Zinmu Rijund runs Dalbit Foundation,
which supports patients

48
00:04:39,028 --> 00:04:41,489
with rare and incurable diseases,
and terminal patients.

49
00:04:42,615 --> 00:04:44,867
DALBIT FOUNDATION

50
00:04:45,493 --> 00:04:48,371
It proved to be
a case of central sensitization.

51
00:04:51,416 --> 00:04:53,418
My impudent explanation is over now.

52
00:04:54,252 --> 00:04:55,753
Thank you for listening.

53
00:04:57,588 --> 00:04:58,548
Lastly,

54
00:04:59,299 --> 00:05:01,426
even though we are introducing CIPA

55
00:05:01,509 --> 00:05:03,553
as a rare and incurable disease
here today,

56
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:05,179
I actually...

57
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:10,476
don't think this disease
is special or unique in any way.

58
00:05:11,894 --> 00:05:15,398
That's because most patients
who come to Pain Management...

59
00:05:16,065 --> 00:05:18,609
suffer from pain which is invisible.

60
00:05:18,985 --> 00:05:21,237
I learned the best way to find the problem

61
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:24,741
in those patients' bodies from Dr. Cha.

62
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:28,411
"Don't look at the symptoms."

63
00:05:28,494 --> 00:05:30,997
"Look at the people
who suffer from those symptoms."

64
00:05:31,789 --> 00:05:35,918
"What doctors treat is not a disease,
but a person."

65
00:05:38,421 --> 00:05:40,715
That's all I have to say. Thank you.

66
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:01,402
Our sales manager will
explain to you in detail.

67
00:06:01,486 --> 00:06:02,570
Just a second.

68
00:06:02,820 --> 00:06:04,781
Give the brochures to the professors.

69
00:06:04,864 --> 00:06:06,324
Go to your positions right now.

70
00:06:06,491 --> 00:06:07,575
-Mr. Jung.
-Yes?

71
00:06:07,784 --> 00:06:09,160
This man...

72
00:06:12,038 --> 00:06:14,248
Thank you. Here.

73
00:06:14,457 --> 00:06:15,875
Thank you. Thank you.

74
00:06:19,712 --> 00:06:21,798
Si-young, that was impressive.

75
00:06:21,881 --> 00:06:23,132
Didn't know you and Dr. Cha

76
00:06:23,216 --> 00:06:25,301
had planned that you'd take over
in the middle.

77
00:06:27,887 --> 00:06:28,888
Si-young, good job.

78
00:06:29,764 --> 00:06:32,225
-Aunt.
-Your presentation was amazing.

79
00:06:32,308 --> 00:06:33,726
I was so surprised.

80
00:06:34,185 --> 00:06:36,187
By the way, is Dr. Cha sick?

81
00:06:37,730 --> 00:06:39,982
He probably felt dizzy for a moment.

82
00:06:40,441 --> 00:06:41,692
He looks fine now.

83
00:06:42,735 --> 00:06:44,320
Let me introduce you to them later.

84
00:06:44,487 --> 00:06:45,446
Thank you.

85
00:06:46,197 --> 00:06:47,990
Does he have stage fright or something?

86
00:06:51,994 --> 00:06:53,871
Why can't he stop finding fault?

87
00:06:54,956 --> 00:06:56,165
Thank you all for today.

88
00:06:56,541 --> 00:06:58,292
-See you.
-See you.

89
00:07:00,128 --> 00:07:03,589
Is Dr. Cha really not feeling well?

90
00:07:04,382 --> 00:07:07,009
Something definitely didn't feel right.
He looked pale.

91
00:07:07,593 --> 00:07:09,846
All right. You can all wait outside.

92
00:07:09,929 --> 00:07:12,515
I'll come with Dr. Cha later
when we're done in here.

93
00:07:12,598 --> 00:07:13,808
-Okay.
-Okay.

94
00:07:21,190 --> 00:07:22,233
Si-young.

95
00:07:23,985 --> 00:07:25,153
Come here for a moment.

96
00:07:35,246 --> 00:07:37,165
The professors here are curious about you.

97
00:07:37,623 --> 00:07:38,624
Say hello.

98
00:07:40,126 --> 00:07:41,252
Hello, I'm...

99
00:07:41,335 --> 00:07:43,588
You don't need to introduce
yourself again.

100
00:07:43,671 --> 00:07:46,591
It's just that we've never seen
a competent resident like you,

101
00:07:46,674 --> 00:07:48,301
so we wanted to meet you in person.

102
00:07:49,969 --> 00:07:51,637
Thank you for your kind words.

103
00:07:52,138 --> 00:07:53,973
I'll see you at the next symposium.

104
00:07:54,056 --> 00:07:55,266
See you.

105
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:57,143
-See you.
-Thank you.

106
00:07:59,187 --> 00:08:00,062
See you again.

107
00:08:01,355 --> 00:08:02,398
Thank you.

108
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:30,927
-Thank you for today.
-Jeez.

109
00:08:31,802 --> 00:08:35,348
I'm sorry. I'm Jung Chan-seok,
sales manager at Zinmu Rijund.

110
00:08:35,806 --> 00:08:36,641
I see.

111
00:08:38,142 --> 00:08:39,143
Here, doctor.

112
00:08:41,145 --> 00:08:43,022
I'll see you again.

113
00:08:46,317 --> 00:08:47,652
What is this?

114
00:08:48,945 --> 00:08:50,530
Where are Dr. Cha and Si-young?

115
00:08:50,821 --> 00:08:52,240
They told us to leave first.

116
00:08:52,949 --> 00:08:54,325
-Let's go.
-Okay.

117
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:55,743
Let's go.

118
00:09:07,630 --> 00:09:09,131
I should probably listen to you.

119
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:11,300
I need to see a doctor.

120
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:13,511
Did you hear a ringing
in your ears earlier?

121
00:09:14,470 --> 00:09:15,596
Yes.

122
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,808
What about now? Are you running a fever?

123
00:09:26,899 --> 00:09:27,900
I don't know.

124
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:31,696
Even if I touch my forehead,
I can't tell...

125
00:09:32,154 --> 00:09:34,198
whether it's hot or cold.

126
00:10:01,809 --> 00:10:04,145
You don't seem to have a fever,
so that's good.

127
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:07,189
-Still, you should see a doctor--
-When I saw you earlier,...

128
00:10:07,898 --> 00:10:11,527
I couldn't tell whether or not
you were actually there.

129
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:14,030
"I'm here."

130
00:10:15,531 --> 00:10:19,285
I thought I heard you say that,
but I wasn't sure.

131
00:10:23,456 --> 00:10:24,582
But I just believed it.

132
00:10:27,209 --> 00:10:28,961
I believed you'd be there.

133
00:10:31,255 --> 00:10:32,131
I believed...

134
00:10:33,174 --> 00:10:35,343
you'd say that to me.

135
00:10:38,929 --> 00:10:40,014
I'll admit it.

136
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:42,725
I need your help.

137
00:10:46,520 --> 00:10:47,730
Thank you in advance.

138
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:55,655
My pleasure.

139
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:06,582
I think I should call it a day.

140
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:09,210
Are you going to see a doctor?

141
00:11:09,877 --> 00:11:11,003
Yes.

142
00:11:12,380 --> 00:11:13,422
See you.

143
00:11:18,427 --> 00:11:19,345
Dr. Cha.

144
00:11:21,931 --> 00:11:23,391
Everything will be all right.

145
00:11:25,393 --> 00:11:27,269
Call me after seeing the doctor.

146
00:12:13,941 --> 00:12:15,901
ANESTHESIOLOGY AND PAIN MANAGEMENT
SYMPOSIUM

147
00:12:32,585 --> 00:12:35,254
GYEONGSEO UNIVERSITY HOSPITAL

148
00:12:35,463 --> 00:12:37,465
HEARING TEST ROOM

149
00:13:27,431 --> 00:13:28,432
How does it look?

150
00:13:29,683 --> 00:13:32,019
I'd like to run a few more tests.

151
00:13:32,436 --> 00:13:35,064
An MRI, a brain CT,
a cerebrovascular CT, and so on.

152
00:13:36,690 --> 00:13:39,235
Do you see what I mean?

153
00:13:42,196 --> 00:13:43,864
Let's do everything that we can.

154
00:13:46,033 --> 00:13:49,578
How much time do I have left...

155
00:13:50,204 --> 00:13:51,372
to live as a doctor?

156
00:14:04,635 --> 00:14:06,804
FOREBODING ON A CRISP AFTERNOON

157
00:15:02,818 --> 00:15:04,820
You're checking your phone
every 30 seconds.

158
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:06,447
What are you looking at?

159
00:15:08,324 --> 00:15:09,158
Great work today.

160
00:15:09,241 --> 00:15:11,952
Dr. Cha has left.
Is there something wrong with him?

161
00:15:13,162 --> 00:15:15,039
I don't know exactly.

162
00:15:15,164 --> 00:15:17,333
He just said it was something personal.

163
00:15:18,125 --> 00:15:21,086
All right. To wrap up today,
should we go for a drink?

164
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:24,256
-What do you think?
-That sounds good.

165
00:15:25,966 --> 00:15:28,135
You're busted.
You're seeing someone, right?

166
00:15:28,218 --> 00:15:29,428
Who's the guy? Who is he?

167
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:31,764
I have to go. I'll see you all tomorrow.

168
00:15:33,974 --> 00:15:36,185
-What is she...
-She's definitely seeing someone.

169
00:15:36,268 --> 00:15:38,103
Right? I have to follow her.

170
00:15:38,604 --> 00:15:39,772
Dr. Heo.

171
00:15:40,272 --> 00:15:42,274
Let's go grab some beers.

172
00:15:42,650 --> 00:15:43,567
Let's go!

173
00:15:43,651 --> 00:15:44,735
-Let's go.
-Let's go.

174
00:15:44,818 --> 00:15:45,819
Let's go.

175
00:15:48,822 --> 00:15:50,783
ANESTHESIOLOGY AND PAIN MANAGEMENT
SYMPOSIUM

176
00:15:51,367 --> 00:15:53,494
Let's eat. I'm hungry.

177
00:15:56,413 --> 00:15:58,540
Dr. Cha, I just got out.

178
00:15:58,958 --> 00:16:00,209
Where should we meet?

179
00:16:15,933 --> 00:16:17,184
This tastes fantastic.

180
00:16:17,893 --> 00:16:20,396
How long are you planning
to work at this hospital?

181
00:16:20,604 --> 00:16:21,438
I'm not sure.

182
00:16:21,522 --> 00:16:23,774
I'll stay until
they make me assistant professor.

183
00:16:23,941 --> 00:16:27,528
An assistant professor? I didn't
know you were the academic type.

184
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:28,821
You don't look like one.

185
00:16:28,904 --> 00:16:30,072
Then what do I look like?

186
00:16:30,155 --> 00:16:31,448
Well...

187
00:16:31,740 --> 00:16:34,451
Maybe the type that starts a clinic
and becomes filthy rich?

188
00:16:35,703 --> 00:16:37,329
The population is aging.

189
00:16:37,454 --> 00:16:42,376
If you start a clinic,
elderly people will line up like...

190
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:43,961
Please remember me then.

191
00:16:44,461 --> 00:16:46,839
Didn't you want to focus
on anesthesiology, not pain?

192
00:16:46,922 --> 00:16:49,925
Exactly. You said patients in pain
made you depressed.

193
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:53,012
Well, since Dr. Cha came,

194
00:16:53,137 --> 00:16:55,097
our Pain Department
has become more dynamic.

195
00:16:55,180 --> 00:16:57,016
It's rewarding and fun to learn and grow,

196
00:16:57,141 --> 00:16:59,309
if you ask me. Oh, my.

197
00:16:59,393 --> 00:17:02,354
"It feels rewarding and fun"? That's nice.

198
00:17:02,438 --> 00:17:03,981
I really don't know.

199
00:17:04,231 --> 00:17:06,191
What are you looking at the whole time?

200
00:17:06,316 --> 00:17:07,526
You dating someone too?

201
00:17:07,609 --> 00:17:10,446
You'd better not date anyone.
Especially your colleagues.

202
00:17:10,529 --> 00:17:12,573
Who would want to date
within our department?

203
00:17:12,823 --> 00:17:15,451
I'm not dating anyone.
You guys should take a look at this.

204
00:17:17,953 --> 00:17:19,413
There's this organization called

205
00:17:19,496 --> 00:17:21,582
The Ambulance Wish Foundation
in Netherlands.

206
00:17:21,665 --> 00:17:23,459
They grant wishes for terminal patients.

207
00:17:23,834 --> 00:17:25,294
I also saw that video.

208
00:17:25,377 --> 00:17:26,754
There's this terminal patient

209
00:17:26,837 --> 00:17:29,506
who applied because he had
something he wanted to do.

210
00:17:29,923 --> 00:17:30,841
And?

211
00:17:32,009 --> 00:17:35,137
And his wish was to go to the beach
and eat ice cream.

212
00:17:35,387 --> 00:17:36,805
Yes, it's him.

213
00:17:40,100 --> 00:17:41,393
That's kind of sad.

214
00:17:41,935 --> 00:17:44,063
I feel like people would
ask for something big

215
00:17:44,146 --> 00:17:45,272
before they die.

216
00:17:45,814 --> 00:17:47,191
But that's such a simple wish.

217
00:17:49,985 --> 00:17:51,737
Patient wanted to go to an art gallery.

218
00:17:52,780 --> 00:17:54,740
This patient wanted to watch

219
00:17:54,865 --> 00:17:56,533
his favorite player play soccer.

220
00:17:56,617 --> 00:17:58,494
This patient wanted to visit his hometown.

221
00:17:58,952 --> 00:18:01,080
They all wished for simple things.

222
00:18:01,789 --> 00:18:04,374
Yes, they just missed
the days when they were healthy.

223
00:18:07,419 --> 00:18:08,545
So I've been thinking...

224
00:18:10,589 --> 00:18:11,840
We should do this as well.

225
00:18:12,216 --> 00:18:13,592
-Do what?
-For whom?

226
00:18:13,675 --> 00:18:15,719
-For Ms. Yoo Ri-hye.
-What?

227
00:18:16,011 --> 00:18:17,846
I was a huge fan.

228
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:20,057
She really made me happy.

229
00:18:20,140 --> 00:18:23,727
But she's sick now,
and she's going to die soon.

230
00:18:24,812 --> 00:18:27,689
Meanwhile, I'm a doctor,
but there's nothing I can do.

231
00:18:29,066 --> 00:18:30,317
This is so touching.

232
00:18:32,361 --> 00:18:33,779
Do you guys really mean it?

233
00:18:34,988 --> 00:18:36,198
Why not?

234
00:18:36,990 --> 00:18:39,243
Who knows? There might
be something we can do.

235
00:18:39,326 --> 00:18:40,452
-Really?
-Yes.

236
00:18:40,661 --> 00:18:41,912
-I'm all for it.
-Me too.

237
00:18:41,995 --> 00:18:43,539
-Deal.
-We're doing this now?

238
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:46,333
-One, two, three. Deal.
-Deal.

239
00:18:46,416 --> 00:18:48,210
I'd like one egg salad sandwich...

240
00:18:48,502 --> 00:18:50,671
and one barbecue chicken sandwich.

241
00:18:59,555 --> 00:19:01,807
Lettuce, tomatoes,...

242
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:04,518
and onions.

243
00:19:38,343 --> 00:19:39,970
-Thank you.
-Bye.

244
00:19:53,734 --> 00:19:54,902
Where are we going?

245
00:20:00,741 --> 00:20:02,117
How about the park nearby?

246
00:20:03,535 --> 00:20:04,578
Let's go.

247
00:20:21,845 --> 00:20:23,138
My gosh, it's beautiful.

248
00:20:24,389 --> 00:20:26,141
Bye. I'm going to beat you.

249
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:28,685
-No.
-You guys can go that way.

250
00:20:30,604 --> 00:20:31,605
Wait for me.

251
00:20:48,288 --> 00:20:50,749
-You're overreacting.
-No, I'm not. I'm being careful.

252
00:20:51,166 --> 00:20:52,584
It doesn't hurt to be careful.

253
00:20:53,001 --> 00:20:55,462
Don't you remember saying,
"Do you have hypochondria?"

254
00:20:55,545 --> 00:20:56,588
Well...

255
00:20:57,005 --> 00:21:00,008
I didn't know anything back then.

256
00:21:01,009 --> 00:21:03,845
And I didn't sound that mean.

257
00:21:08,433 --> 00:21:09,810
What did the doctor say?

258
00:21:13,522 --> 00:21:14,564
Dr. Cha.

259
00:21:15,941 --> 00:21:17,109
I took a few tests.

260
00:21:17,192 --> 00:21:19,278
He's going to call me
once he gets the results

261
00:21:19,361 --> 00:21:20,779
for a comprehensive checkup.

262
00:21:21,196 --> 00:21:22,698
You got a comprehensive checkup?

263
00:21:23,115 --> 00:21:25,409
Yes, just in case.

264
00:21:25,993 --> 00:21:27,911
-Is that all?
-Yes.

265
00:21:31,873 --> 00:21:33,625
We should sit down and eat.

266
00:21:34,209 --> 00:21:35,711
You said you wanted to eat this.

267
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:45,512
Have you wanted to be a doctor
since you were young?

268
00:21:46,638 --> 00:21:47,681
No.

269
00:21:48,390 --> 00:21:49,933
Then what did you want to become?

270
00:21:53,270 --> 00:21:54,855
I wanted to own a comic book store.

271
00:21:56,732 --> 00:21:57,816
A comic book store?

272
00:21:59,151 --> 00:22:02,446
We used to have an attic in our old house.

273
00:22:03,196 --> 00:22:04,197
And?

274
00:22:04,448 --> 00:22:06,867
Every time I read comic books there,

275
00:22:07,159 --> 00:22:10,537
I felt really comfortable.
It felt like I was in another world.

276
00:22:12,622 --> 00:22:13,874
That suits you.

277
00:22:15,751 --> 00:22:17,461
What do you think would've suited me?

278
00:22:20,255 --> 00:22:21,715
I can't really imagine anything else.

279
00:22:22,758 --> 00:22:24,259
I can't really imagine you...

280
00:22:24,968 --> 00:22:27,679
as anything other than a doctor.

281
00:22:28,930 --> 00:22:30,098
Really?

282
00:22:32,017 --> 00:22:33,101
But why do you ask?

283
00:22:34,686 --> 00:22:35,812
No reason.

284
00:22:36,980 --> 00:22:40,901
I figured I might have to quit
being a doctor one day.

285
00:22:42,652 --> 00:22:46,114
But I've never really thought about
what I should do after I quit.

286
00:22:46,823 --> 00:22:47,949
You're going to quit?

287
00:22:49,409 --> 00:22:50,702
You're not going to quit, right?

288
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:52,454
I'm just saying.

289
00:22:53,580 --> 00:22:56,166
You have to tell me if anything happens.

290
00:22:57,417 --> 00:22:58,418
Okay?

291
00:22:58,960 --> 00:23:00,587
Okay, I promise.

292
00:23:06,134 --> 00:23:09,846
